name: [1] Floating Torii Gate of Oouo Shrine
Saga Beef
flavor_text: Exquisitely marbled beef. Product of nature-rich Saga Prefecture and cattle-fattening farmers. Only A4 and A5 beef with a 7 or higher Beef Marbling Score can be named Saga Beef. The first frost of the year is likened to a "majestic fatty slice of beef".

name: Takezaki Crab
flavor_text: A special commodity of Saga Prefecture. Found in the muds of Tara, a town at the southernmost tip of Saga. Mainly caught in the Takezaki region by the Ariake Sea. A kind of portunid crab known as the Japanese blue crab.

name: Gatalympics
flavor_text: Located in the Ariake Sea, which has the largest tidal range in Japan. A festival for getting covered in mud while competing in unique events such as the mud board competition, a bike race in the mud flats, and a human mudskipper race.

name: Yobuko Squid
flavor_text: Located in the Genkai Sea. The warm Tsushima Current makes it a good place for catching squid. A great deal of swordtip squid endemic to certain areas of Japan are found here. Yobuko in Karatsu City got its fame for serving live squid.

name: Karatsu Kunchi
flavor_text: 3-day "Yama, Hoko and Yatai Float Festival" at the Karatsu Shrine. Shouts of "Enya, enya!" and "Yoisa, yoisa!" follow hikiyama festival floats through the old castle town. On UNESCO's Representative List of the Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity.

name: Ureshino Onsen
flavor_text: Top three hot spring in Japan for skin care. One dip in the silky water and you'll never want to leave. Experience the local history and customs at the densely clustered traditional inns, then try the local dish of hot spring soup tofu after a relaxing soak.

name: Sagan Tosu FC
flavor_text: Football club located in Tosu and currently playing in the J1 League. On the team logo is written "True champions in the hearts of all who love Sagantosu."

name: Kyushu Saga International Airport
flavor_text: A budget airline that has garnered attention in recent years for offering direct flights to all over Asia, as well as for its flights to Narita International Airport.

name: Arita Ware
flavor_text: The prime example of Saga artisanry. Give it as a present to others or keep it for yourself. The gorgeous luster and richly-detailed designs make it perfect for any use.

name: Nanatsugama
flavor_text: Sea caves designated as a National Natural Monument. The array of seven caves lining the rock lead you to a mystical world not unlike the Blue Cave in Okinawa. To get there, just take a ferry from Yobuko.

name: Niji No Matsubara
flavor_text: One of the three great pine groves of Japan. 4.5 km long and 0.5 km wide, roughly 1 million Japanese black pines have been planted here. Take in the scenery of the entire grove from the top of Mount Kagami. Said to feature its own set of Seven Wonders.

name: Saga Prefectural Government Office
flavor_text: Romancing headquarters in Saga Prefecture. From the building, the view of the land and skies opens up before you. Watch the setting sun stain the streets red while enjoying a nice meal at the visitor's restaurant.

name: Ekimae Real Estate Stadium
flavor_text: The home stadium for Sagan Tosu FC of the J1 League. Local fans have come to calling it by a shorter name, "Ekisuta".

name: Takeo Onsen
flavor_text: Reportedly visited by Miyamoto Musashi and Philipp Franz von Siebold. Ideal spot to help revitalize the mind and body. The red-lacquered gate designed by Tatsuno Kingo, architect of Tokyo Station, resembles the Ryugo-jo, a legendary undersea palace.

name: Yoshinogari Historical Park
flavor_text: Moat settlement ruins from the Yayoi Period. The watchtower and pit dwellings have been restored to their original likeness. When first opened to the public in 1989, a sighting of Queen Himiko, ruler of Yamatai, was a popular topic of conversation.

name: Yutoku Inari Shrine
flavor_text: Considered one of the top three Inari shrines and known by locals as "Miss Yutoku". The most impressive feature is the red buildings whose roofs reflect a leafy green. Famous for the god of fortune who watches over merchants. Flocks of believers visit every year.

name: Karatsu Castle
flavor_text: Symbol of Karatsu City. The "tenshu" (highest tower in a castle) is like the head of a crane, with the surrounding pine grove like the wings. It is thus called "Dancing Crane Castle". From afar, the beautiful tower is set ablaze by the flames of lanterns.

name: Lake Kitayama
flavor_text: Largest artificial lake in Saga Prefecture. A favorite fishing spot for many and one of the few fishing lakes in Kyushu. Features a 6 km bike path, tennis courts, a lakeside camping area, an exercise park, and many other facilities for enjoying the great outdoors.

name: Karatsu Line (Karatsu Station)
flavor_text: A one-way rail running 42.5 km from Saga's Kubota Station to Karatsu's Nishi Karatsu Station. Built in 1898 to transport coal from northern Saga to Karatsu Port. No longer used for coal mining, the tracks are now but two legs stretching off into the distance.

name: Karatsu Line (Saga Station)
flavor_text: A one-way rail running 42.5 km from Saga's Kubota Station to Karatsu's Nishi Karatsu Station. Built in 1898 to transport coal from northern Saga to Karatsu Port. No longer used for coal mining, the tracks are now but two legs stretching off into the distance.

name: Okuma Shigenobu (Statue)
flavor_text: One of the Seven Heroes-- no, Sages-- of Saga. Was Prime Minister of Japan and founded Waseda University. Okuma Memorial Museum holds his statue and other valuable relics. The museum also preserves the look of his hometown samurai village.

name: Nanatsugama
flavor_text: The Nanatsugama Caves, designated as a natural monument of Japan, are spectacular caves formed by the raging waves of the Genkai Sea. The name is indicative of its 7 caves, and the scenery strikes onlookers by the wonders of nature.

name: Nagoya Castle Ruins
flavor_text: Surrounding the ruins of Nagoya Castle itself for a 3 km radius, these ruins were home to over 160 of Japan's feudal lords, making it one of Japan's largest and unique ruins. Ongoing surveys and maintenance continue at the Nagoya Castle Ruins and surrounding camp sites.

name: Q Saba Mackerel
flavor_text: Joint research by Kyushu University and Karatsu City created this farm-raised mackerel with exceptional flavor. It lacks the fishy odor of wild-caught mackerel and offers a delightful balance of fat and taste. Enjoy it as sashimi or try other variations like sesame or seared mackerel.

name: Tonbai Wall & Arita Ware
flavor_text: Tonbai walls are created by applying red clay to discarded fireproof bricks (tonbai) used in climbing kilns. These walls can be found in the alleys around Izumiyama Ooicho and the Arita Ceramic Museum in Odaru. They add to the charm of the pottery town, showcasing the legacy of kiln construction and disposal.

name: Imari Station
flavor_text: This station in western Saga Prefecture connects the Chikuhi and Nishi-Kyushu lines. It's a landmark with its design motifs featuring the white plaster walls of pottery dealers and the chimneys of the "kamado" pottery kilns, reflecting its past as a busy pottery shipping port in the Edo period.

name: Taku Station
flavor_text: This station in the heart of Saga Prefecture serves the Karatsu line. It is located near the community development center "Aiparetto," which aims to create a vibrant community in a compact space near Taku Station. This name was chosen through public contributions as a lovable nickname.

name: Furuyu Onsen
flavor_text: Located along the Kasegawa river in Fuji town, the legendary Furuyu Onsen was discovered by Xu Fu around 2,100 years ago while searching for the elixir of life. The alkaline, simple hot spring with a slight viscosity is renowned for its effectiveness in relieving joint pain.

name: Ogi Station
flavor_text: Ogi Station was built to coincide with the opening of the Karatsu line in 1903. Recognized as a tangible cultural property, it features a framed calligraphic name by renowned local calligrapher Gochiku Nakabayashi, welcoming visitors at the entrance.

name: Takanawa Embankment Exhibition
flavor_text: Japan's first railroad opened for business in 1872. This is the Takanawa embankment, associated with Okuma Shigenobu, constructed so the railroad could go over the sea. A segment discovered in 2022 is on display at Okuma's birthplace of Saga in the Saga Prefectural Museum.

name: Saga Station
flavor_text: This station is in Saga City, capital of Saga Prefecture. Tabidachi Ebisu is found on the platform expressing the wish to "watch over those who come to Saga, those who leave Saga, and those who pass through Saga station." In front of the station stands a statue of Menfuryu, a form of folk entertainment.
